            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The seceding states explicitly cited slavery as the cause. Mississippi's declaration states: 'Our position is thoroughly identified with the institution of slaveryâ€”the greatest material interest of the world.' Georgia's declaration mentions slavery over 80 times. Tariffs are rarely or never mentioned in these documents."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What was the Southern Strategy?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The Southern Strategy was a Republican electoral strategy to win white Southern voters by appealing to racial resentment. Nixon adviser Kevin Phillips outlined it in 1970. Lee Atwater later explained how it evolved from explicit racism to coded language like 'states' rights' and 'forced busing.' RNC Chairman Ken Mehlman apologized for it in 2005."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Didn't more Republicans vote for the Civil Rights Act?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, but this is misleading. The real divide was regional, not partisan: Northern Democrats voted 94% yes, while Southern Democrats voted only 7% yes. It was North vs South, not Republican vs Democrat. And those Southern Democrats who opposed civil rights? Their voters became Republicans over the following decades, which is exactly what the party switch describes."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What about Robert Byrd?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
